WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.280
Let's understand Conditional Co-Ablation — a way to find the hidden backup parts of a model's reasoning, from the ground up.

00:00:08.280 --> 00:00:12.440
A language model reads a sentence and predicts the next word.

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:19.080
Inside, small components called attention heads each carry out a little piece of that computation.

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:24.070
Here, a few heads copy the name Mary to the output as the prediction.

00:00:24.070 --> 00:00:28.390
The specific heads that carry one behavior are called its circuit.

00:00:28.390 --> 00:00:36.260
To find them, researchers delete a component and watch how much the answer changes. A big drop means it mattered.

00:00:36.260 --> 00:00:39.500
But here is the trap that motivates our work.

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:45.450
Delete an important head, and a dormant backup silently takes over and re-routes the answer.

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:54.830
The output barely changes. So the deleted head looks unimportant — and the backup, silent before, looks unimportant too.

00:00:54.830 --> 00:01:00.980
Deleting a group is not the sum of deleting its parts, and standard scoring misses both sides.

00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:05.800
CoAx fixes this with one idea: don't score a unit on its own.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:10.890
Score how much its effect grows once the main parts have already been removed.

00:01:10.890 --> 00:01:15.760
A backup does almost nothing by itself — its effect is near zero.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:25.430
But once its partner is removed, its effect becomes large. That growth is the CoAx score, and it needs no labels and no gradients.

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:30.360
Measured over every pair of heads, the interactions reveal a hidden module:

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:37.850
the main heads and their backups, wired in parallel — exactly what a one-head-at-a-time score cannot see.

00:01:37.850 --> 00:01:45.190
So does it work? On a circuit with known backups, we rank all the heads and check the eight documented ones.

00:01:45.190 --> 00:01:54.880
Single-ablation scoring sits below chance at 0.33; even gradient methods built for self-repair top out at 0.82.

00:01:54.880 --> 00:02:01.380
CoAx reaches 0.91 — moving the backups from the blind spot to the top of the ranking.

00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:10.140
And they really are backups. As we remove the main heads one by one, the discovered heads wake up and start writing the answer,

00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:18.120
while random heads stay flat. Freezing them undoes the repair — proof they cause it, not just correlate with it.

00:02:18.120 --> 00:02:29.030
Zoom into a single backup: it is silent on the clean model, yet it already reads the correct name, and becomes load-bearing only once its primary is gone.

00:02:29.030 --> 00:02:33.080
This blind spot hides inside the tools everyone uses.

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:47.080
Fed the recovered backups, attribution, capability removal, and pruning are all repaired — pruning here wins at every scale, from 124 million to 7 billion parameters.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:58.370
And it is not one lucky circuit: the same label-free method transfers to a second circuit, induction, across eight further models and six architecture families.

00:02:58.370 --> 00:03:02.750
So a component's importance is not fixed — it is conditional.

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:13.040
The parts that matter most are often the ones that stay silent until they are needed. Code, an interactive page, and the paper are linked on screen.
